2008/9/17 Jan Kroeze &lt;thejcwk@...&gt;:
&gt; Hi!
&gt;
&gt; I think I understand your point #1, but I&#39;m not quite sure. Why was it
&gt; difficult to locate the specific tests?

FIT lets you mix tests and freeform text, write documents that link to
tests, index tests in different ways, etc. etc.  That&#39;s harder to do
with JUnit.  We could have linked from our wiki to JUnit tests in
Subversion, which would have helped but made refactoring more
difficult.

&gt; Your second point has been mentioned by quite a few people on the list.
&gt; Would I be correct if I thought of this factor as a major factor in making
&gt; the decision to migrate to FIT or something similar?

It&#39;s one of many factors.  Refactoring and tool support are also
factors to take into account.

&gt;
&gt; 2008/9/14 Nat Pryce &lt;nat.pryce@...&gt;
&gt;
&gt;&gt; I&#39;ve used JUnit for system testing as well as unit testing.
&gt;&gt;
&gt;&gt; It worked pretty well -- JUnit has great tool support, is small and
&gt;&gt; simple and, being plain old Java, is easy to extend or plug onto
&gt;&gt; existing APIs and external systems.
&gt;&gt;
&gt;&gt; The two main drawbacks we found were:
&gt;&gt;
&gt;&gt; 1) Too hard to go back and find out about the system behaviour from
&gt;&gt; the tests. We refactored our tests agressively into a &quot;domain
&gt;&gt; specific embedded language&quot; for describing business rules, but it was
&gt;&gt; difficult to find the test(s) we needed to read to understand why the
&gt;&gt; system did what it did.
&gt;&gt;
&gt;
&gt;&gt;
&gt;&gt; 2) A JUnit test aborts completely on failure. For system tests, we
&gt;&gt; wanted to distinguish between fatal failures that should abort the
&gt;&gt; test, and failures that allowed the test to continue running. For
&gt;&gt; example, a system that displays calculations in a table should fail
&gt;&gt; the test if any calculations are incorrect and report *all* the
&gt;&gt; incorrect calculations, not abort as soon as it detects a single
&gt;&gt; incorrect calculation.
&gt;&gt;
&gt;&gt; FIT and similar tools address these issues much better than JUnit, but
&gt;&gt; you sacrifice easy refactoring.
&gt;&gt;
&gt;&gt; --Nat
&gt;&gt;
&gt;&gt; 2008/9/8 Jan Kroeze &lt;thejcwk@... &lt;thejcwk%40gmail.com&gt;&gt;:
&gt;&gt;
&gt;&gt; &gt; Hi!
&gt;&gt; &gt;
&gt;&gt; &gt; Very good point about acceptance testing and system boundaries. I hadn&#39;t
&gt;&gt; &gt; thought of this and people often forget to mention it. Of course, this
&gt;&gt; has a
&gt;&gt; &gt; great effect on the tools you end up using.
&gt;&gt; &gt;
&gt;&gt; &gt; Also, I agree regarding the combinatorial explosion problem. I had to
&gt;&gt; write
&gt;&gt; &gt; a Lexer for a toy programming language in one of my courses and having a
&gt;&gt; &gt; unit test for each input pattern helped to narrow down problems so
&gt;&gt; quickly
&gt;&gt; &gt; that I finished in ~3 hours!
&gt;&gt; &gt;
&gt;&gt; &gt; People here at varsity also seldom miss the point about testing scope.
&gt;&gt; They
&gt;&gt; &gt; seem to assume that every level of testing will always be used, and
&gt;&gt; &gt; teach
&gt;&gt; &gt; accordingly. I think it&#39;s important to note that this is not always
&gt;&gt; &gt; neccessary.
&gt;&gt; &gt;
&gt;&gt; &gt; Thanks for the distinction you made between integration tests and larger
&gt;&gt; &gt; scale ones. I think I understand a little better where the boundaries
&gt;&gt; &gt; lie
&gt;&gt; :)
&gt;&gt; &gt;
&gt;&gt; &gt; 2008/9/4 lancezant &lt;lancezant@... &lt;lancezant%40hotmail.com&gt;&gt;
&gt;&gt; &gt;
&gt;&gt; &gt;&gt; Hi Jan,
&gt;&gt; &gt;&gt;
&gt;&gt; &gt;&gt; I agree, and as you touch on the idea of acceptance tests, you come
&gt;&gt; &gt;&gt; close to the one point I&#39;d add. Besides running time and number of
&gt;&gt; &gt;&gt; failures, the other distinguishing feature of acceptance tests is that
&gt;&gt; &gt;&gt; the interacts often cross the system&#39;s boundary. By that I mean input
&gt;&gt; &gt;&gt; comes through non-java interfaces such as GUIs, message systems, etc.
&gt;&gt; &gt;&gt; and output involve more side effects (i.e. go to places other than
&gt;&gt; &gt;&gt; back to the source). In some cases, these can be shoehorned into a
&gt;&gt; &gt;&gt; Java interface (e.g. httpunit) but this is often where the need for
&gt;&gt; &gt;&gt; other tools comes in.
&gt;&gt; &gt;&gt;
&gt;&gt; &gt;&gt; The reason for fine-grained testing is that large-grained tests are
&gt;&gt; &gt;&gt; overwhelmed by combinatoric explosion of conditions long before they
&gt;&gt; &gt;&gt; achieve reasonable coverage. The &quot;unit&quot; is usually a single class.
&gt;&gt; &gt;&gt; The system can be tens to thousands of classes. For small systems,
&gt;&gt; &gt;&gt; the gap may be small enough that unit and acceptance tests are
&gt;&gt; &gt;&gt; sufficient.
&gt;&gt; &gt;&gt;
&gt;&gt; &gt;&gt; Often, however, it is useful to have integration tests in between. By
&gt;&gt; &gt;&gt; testing clusters of collaborating classes, integration tests can
&gt;&gt; &gt;&gt; further reduce the number of acceptance tests needed to achieve
&gt;&gt; &gt;&gt; reasonable coverage. The thing integration tests have in common with
&gt;&gt; &gt;&gt; unit tests is that by being entirely within the system boundary, they
&gt;&gt; &gt;&gt; can reuse much of the Java infrastructure, including JUnit, mock
&gt;&gt; &gt;&gt; objects, etc.
&gt;&gt; &gt;&gt;
&gt;&gt; &gt;&gt; Best regards,
&gt;&gt; &gt;&gt; Lance
&gt;&gt; &gt;&gt;
