&gt;&gt; &gt;&gt; &lt;thejcwk@...&gt; wrote:
&gt;&gt; &gt;&gt; &gt;
&gt;&gt; &gt;&gt; &gt; Hi!
&gt;&gt; &gt;&gt; &gt;
&gt;&gt; &gt;&gt; &gt; I think this summarises quite neatly what a couple of people have
&gt;&gt; &gt;&gt; said,
&gt;&gt; &gt;&gt; &gt; namely that switching to a dedicated framework from JUnit is only
&gt;&gt; &gt;&gt; neccessary
&gt;&gt; &gt;&gt; &gt; if there are quite a few / complicated integration tests.
&gt;&gt; &gt;&gt; &gt;
&gt;&gt; &gt;&gt; &gt; I happen to agree with this, since introducing more and more
&gt;&gt; &gt;&gt; frameworks into
&gt;&gt; &gt;&gt; &gt; your project just for testing will certainly drive many programmers
&gt;&gt; &gt;&gt; up the
&gt;&gt; &gt;&gt; &gt; walls. You have to be certain the cost is worth the pay off :) Yet,
&gt;&gt; &gt;&gt; &gt; especially with user acceptance testing, I have to side with going
&gt;&gt; &gt;&gt; with a
&gt;&gt; &gt;&gt; &gt; new framework, if simply for the reason that the client should be
&gt;&gt; &gt;&gt; able to
&gt;&gt; &gt;&gt; &gt; read them.
&gt;&gt; &gt;&gt; &gt;
&gt;&gt; &gt;&gt; &gt; 2008/9/3 kentb &lt;kentb@...&gt;
&gt;&gt; &gt;&gt;
&gt;&gt; &gt;&gt; &gt;
&gt;&gt; &gt;&gt; &gt; &gt; Jan,
&gt;&gt; &gt;&gt; &gt; &gt;
&gt;&gt; &gt;&gt; &gt; &gt; You can use JUnit for longer-running tests, but there are some
&gt;&gt; &gt;&gt; assumptions
&gt;&gt; &gt;&gt; &gt; &gt; JUnit embodies that will cause some problems. JUnit assumes tests
&gt;&gt; &gt;&gt; are
&gt;&gt; &gt;&gt; &gt; &gt; atomic--they run or don&#39;t run, they run in unit time. Integration
&gt;&gt; &gt;&gt; tests
&gt;&gt; &gt;&gt; &gt; &gt; often take a long time to run, so interim feedback is valuable.
&gt;&gt; &gt;&gt; Integration
&gt;&gt; &gt;&gt; &gt; &gt; tests can usefully have multiple failures, where that is less
&gt;&gt; &gt;&gt; common with
&gt;&gt; &gt;&gt; &gt; &gt; unit tests. OTOH, tests are tests--independent self-checking bits
&gt;&gt; &gt;&gt; of code
&gt;&gt; &gt;&gt; &gt; &gt; that run and get reported--and for that part of running
&gt;&gt; &gt;&gt; integration tests
&gt;&gt; &gt;&gt; &gt; &gt; JUnit works fine.
&gt;&gt; &gt;&gt; &gt; &gt;
&gt;&gt; &gt;&gt; &gt; &gt; It seems to me to be a tradeoff between the simplicity of running
&gt;&gt; &gt;&gt; all tests
&gt;&gt; &gt;&gt; &gt; &gt; as JUnit tests and the challenges of getting the integration tests
&gt;&gt; &gt;&gt; to run
&gt;&gt; &gt;&gt; &gt; &gt; as
&gt;&gt; &gt;&gt; &gt; &gt; JUnit tests. Different contexts will requires different solutions.
&gt;&gt; &gt;&gt; If I had
&gt;&gt; &gt;&gt; &gt; &gt; a few integration tests, I&#39;d make them work with JUnit. If I had a
&gt;&gt; &gt;&gt; large
&gt;&gt; &gt;&gt; &gt; &gt; suite of integration tests that played a prominent role in
&gt;&gt; &gt;&gt; development, I
&gt;&gt; &gt;&gt; &gt; &gt; would use some other tool and integrate my unit testing results
&gt;&gt; &gt;&gt; with the
&gt;&gt; &gt;&gt; &gt; &gt; integration results.
&gt;&gt; &gt;&gt; &gt; &gt;
&gt;&gt; &gt;&gt; &gt; &gt; Regards,
