&gt;&gt; &gt;&gt; &gt; &gt;
&gt;&gt; &gt;&gt; &gt; &gt; Hi all!
&gt;&gt; &gt;&gt; &gt; &gt;
&gt;&gt; &gt;&gt; &gt; &gt; I&#39;m a bit of a newb to the whole TDD thing, but I understand that
&gt;&gt; &gt;&gt; unit
&gt;&gt; &gt;&gt; &gt; &gt; tests
&gt;&gt; &gt;&gt; &gt; &gt; are supposed to be blazingly fast and not access the hard drive,
&gt;&gt; &gt;&gt; network,
&gt;&gt; &gt;&gt; &gt; &gt; database or anything external to the code itself. To this end, I
&gt;&gt; &gt;&gt; understand
&gt;&gt; &gt;&gt; &gt; &gt; that a framework such as jMock can be used.
&gt;&gt; &gt;&gt; &gt; &gt;
&gt;&gt; &gt;&gt; &gt; &gt; So far, so good. But I find JUnit to be extremely useful for
&gt;&gt; &gt;&gt; writing
&gt;&gt; &gt;&gt; &gt; &gt; integration, system and user acceptance tests as well.
&gt;&gt; &gt;&gt; &gt; &gt;
&gt;&gt; &gt;&gt; &gt; &gt; Here&#39;s my question: what is the official position of the JUnit
&gt;&gt; &gt;&gt; community on
&gt;&gt; &gt;&gt; &gt; &gt; using JUnit to do larger scale tests? Is there a better framework,
&gt;&gt; &gt;&gt; or is it
&gt;&gt; &gt;&gt; &gt; &gt; common practice to use JUnit for these tests as well?
&gt;&gt; &gt;&gt; &gt; &gt;
